# Design Engineer Course - Cursor Rules

## British English for All Prose

**IMPORTANT: All user-facing copy, marketing materials, and course content MUST use British English spelling and grammar.**

### When to Use British English
- ✅ All user-facing text, headings, and descriptions
- ✅ Marketing copy on landing pages
- ✅ Course lesson content and explanations
- ✅ Email templates and notifications
- ✅ FAQ, help text, and documentation
- ✅ Button labels and UI microcopy
- ✅ Error messages and success messages
- ✅ Blog posts and articles
- ✅ README files and comments

### When to Use American English
- ✅ Code keywords and syntax (e.g., `color` in CSS, `center` in HTML/CSS)
- ✅ Programming language conventions
- ✅ Framework and library names
- ✅ File paths and technical identifiers
- ✅ Code comments explaining technical implementation
- ✅ Variable names and function names

### Common British English Spellings

**General:**
- customise (not customize)
- organisation (not organization)
- realise (not realize)
- recognise (not recognize)
- analyse (not analyze)
- optimise (not optimize)
- specialise (not specialize)
- categorise (not categorize)

**-our endings:**
- colour (not color) - EXCEPT in CSS properties
- behaviour (not behavior)
- favour (not favor)
- favourite (not favorite)
- honour (not honor)
- neighbour (not neighbor)

**-re endings:**
- centre (not center) - EXCEPT in CSS properties
- theatre (not theater)
- metre (not meter)
- litre (not liter)

**-ce vs -se:**
- defence (not defense)
- offence (not offense)
- licence (noun, not license)
- practise (verb, not practice)

**Other:**
- programme (not program) - for events/courses, BUT "computer program" is acceptable
- grey (not gray)
- aeroplane (not airplane)
- travelled (not traveled)
- modelling (not modeling)
- cancelled (not canceled)
- focussed (not focused) - though both accepted
- whilst (not while) - though both accepted

### Examples

#### Good (British English)
```tsx
<h1>Customise Your Learning Experience</h1>
<p>Whilst learning to code, you'll realise that design and engineering are deeply connected.</p>
<Button>Optimise Your Workflow</Button>
```

#### Bad (Mixed)
```tsx
<h1>Customize Your Learning Experience</h1>
<p>While learning to code, you'll realize that design and engineering are deeply connected.</p>
<Button>Optimize Your Workflow</Button>
```

#### Code is Still American
```css
/* Correct - CSS uses American English */
.button {
  color: red;
  text-align: center;
  background-color: gray;
}
```

```tsx
// Correct - Code uses American English
const backgroundColor = "gray";
function centerElement() {
  // British English in comments explaining to users
  // This function centres the element on the page
  element.style.textAlign = "center"; // American in code
}
```

### Grammar Differences

**Collective nouns:**
- British: "The team are working" (plural)
- American: "The team is working" (singular)
- **Use British style**

**Quotation marks:**
- British: Single quotes for speech, punctuation outside: 'Hello', he said.
- American: Double quotes, punctuation inside: "Hello," he said.
- **Use British style for prose**

**Date format:**
- British: 21 December 2025
- American: December 21, 2025
- **Use British style**

**Prepositions:**
- British: "at the weekend"
- American: "on the weekend"
- **Use British style**

### Currency
- Use £ (GBP) as primary currency
- Format: £199 (no space)
- Spelled out: 199 pounds

### Exceptions

Some Americanisms are acceptable when they're industry standard:
- "Sign up" / "Sign in" (not "Register" / "Log in") - widely understood
- "Email" (not "e-mail") - standard modern usage
- "Website" (not "web site") - standard modern usage
- Technical jargon that's standardised with American spelling

### Automated Checking

When in doubt, prefer British spelling. Consider these resources:
- Oxford English Dictionary for British spellings
- Collins Dictionary
- Cambridge Dictionary

### AI Instructions

When generating or editing content:
1. Always default to British English for user-facing text
2. Keep code-related technical terms in American English
3. Double-check common American/British spelling differences
4. Maintain consistency across the entire codebase
5. When converting existing content, search for common American spellings systematically

